  <title>Examples D</title>
  

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In a double slit interference experiment, the spacing between the slits is <m>10 \,\mu m</m> 
        and the screen is at a distance of 2 m. If light of wavelength 500 nm is used, find 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            the location of the first dark fringe,
          </li>
          <li>
            the location of the third (off axis) bright fringe,
          </li>
          <li>
            the spacing between the fringes,
          </li>
          <li>
            the theoretical maximum number of bright fringes possible. 
          </li>
        </ol>
             </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig79.png" width ="60%"> </image>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <me>
              \Delta x=d\sin\theta = m \frac{\lambda}{2}
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad 10.00\times10^{-6}\sin\theta = \frac{1}{2}500.00\times10^{-9} \Rightarrow \theta = 1.43^{o} 
            </me>
            <me>
              y=D\tan\theta \Rightarrow y = 2\tan(1.43^{o}) \Rightarrow y = 5 \,cm
            </me>
             </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \Delta x=d\sin\theta = m \lambda 
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad 10.00\times10^{-6}\sin\theta = (3)(500.00\times10^{-9}) \Rightarrow \theta = 8.63^{o}
            </me>
            <me>
              y=D\tan\theta \Rightarrow y = 2\tan(8.63^{o}) \Rightarrow y = 30 \,cm
            </me>
               </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \beta = \frac{D\lambda}{d} = 10 \,cm
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{alternate,}\quad 10.00\times10^{-6}\sin\theta =(1) (500\times10^{-9})\Rightarrow \theta = 2.86^{o}
            </me>
            <me>
              y=2\tan 2.86^{o} \Rightarrow y= 10 \,cm
            </me>
                </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \Delta x=d\sin\theta = m \lambda
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad 10.00\times10^{-6}\sin 90^{o} = (m)(500.00\times10^{-9}) \Rightarrow m = 20 
            </me>
            <me>
              m_{total}=2m+1, 
            </me>
           fringes on both sides plus central frings 
            <me>
              \Rightarrow m=41.
            </me>
             </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            What is the minimum thickness of a soap bubble film with index of refraction 1.33 which would reflect most brightly 
            red light of wavelength 650 nm? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the minimum thickness of an anti-reflecting coating of index of refraction 1.4 on a glass lens of index 1.5 
            which would reflect no green light of wavelength 550 nm?
          </li>
          <li>
            What would be the color of the light that is reflected off the lens? 
          </li>
        </ol>
        </p>
         </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig80.png" width ="60%"> </image>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            As I reflected ray is <m>180^{o}</m> out of phase by itself due to reflection from a 
            surface of high refracting medium, so in order to make it interferes constructively 
            with II emergent ray from films the total path difference between these rays must be 
            equal to integral multiple of <m>\lambda/2</m>. 
            <me>
              \therefore \quad 2t=m\frac{\lambda_{film}}{2},
            </me>
            set m = 1 for minimum thickness. 
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad 2t=\frac{\lambda_{film}}{2} \quad \text{for bright fringe}
            </me>
             <me>
              but, n = \frac{c}{v}= \frac{\nu \lambda_{o}}{\nu \lambda_{film}} = \frac{ \lambda_{o}}{ \lambda_{film}} 
             </me>
             <me>
              \Rightarrow \lambda_{film} = \frac{\lambda_{o}}{n_{2}}
             </me>
             <me>
              \text{or,}\quad t=\frac{\lambda_{film}}{4} = \frac{\lambda_{o}}{4 n_{2}}  = \frac{650 \,nm}{4\times1.33} =122 \,nm
             </me>
                 </li>
          <li>
            As I and II rays are <m>180^{o}</m> out of phase due to reflection from a surface of 
            high refracting medium, so in order to make them interfere destructively total path 
            difference between them must be equal to integral multiple of <m>\lambda/2</m>  
            <me>
              \therefore 2t = m\frac{\lambda_{film}}{2}
            </me>
              set m = 1$  for minimum thickness. 
              <me>
                \text{or},\quad t = \frac{\lambda_{film}}{4} = \frac{\lambda_{o}}{4 n_{2}} = \frac{550\,nm}{4\times1.4} =98\,nm
              </me>
                </li>
          <li>
            Since green light is transmitted, red and blue are reflected. Therefore, color reflected is magenta.
          </li>
        </ol> 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A parallel beam of light <m>\lambda=5890 \,\AA </m> is incident on a thin glass plate (n=1.5) 
        such that the angle of refraction into the plate is <m>60^{o}</m>.  Calculate the minimum 
        thickness of the glass plate which will appear dark by reflection.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        For destructive interference by reflected ray, 
        <me>
          2\eta t \cos r = n\lambda
        </me>
        <me>
          \Rightarrow t = \frac{n\lambda}{2 \eta \cos r} = \frac{1\times 5890}{2\times 1.5\times 0.5}=3926 \,\AA; 
        </me>
        for minimum thickness, set n=1.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A beam of parallel rays is incident at an angle of <m>30^{o}</m> with the normal 
        on a plane parallel film of thickness <m>4\times 10^{-5} \,cm</m> and refractive index is 1.5. 
        Show that the reflected light whose wavelength is <m>7.539\times 10^{-5} \,cm,</m> 
        will be strengthened by reinforcement.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        For constructive interference by reflected ray, 
        <me>
          2\eta t \cos r = \frac{n\lambda}{2} 
        </me>
        <me>
          or, \quad n =\frac{4\eta t \cos r}{\lambda}  =\frac{4\times 1.5\times \cos 19.4}{7.539\times 10^{-5} } =3
        </me>
      at <me> i = 30^{o},\quad \eta_{1}\sin i = \eta_{2}\sin r </me> 
       <me> \Rightarrow \sin r = \frac{\sin 30}{1.5} =0.33 </me>
       <me>
         \Rightarrow r= 19.4^{o}.
       </me>
        </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A single slit of width 0.2 mm is illuminated with a beam of laser light of wavelength 600 nm 
        which casts a single slit diffraction pattern on a screen 6 m away. 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            What is the linear spacing between two successive fringes observed on the screen? 
          </li>
          <li>
            How far from the central bright fringe is the 4^{th} dark fringe located?
          </li>
          <li>
            How far from the central (zero^{th}) bright fringe is the first bright fringe located? 
          </li>
        </ol>
             </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
      Given: <m>a=2.0\times10^{-4}\,m; \quad \lambda= 6.0\times10^{-7}\,m; \quad D = 6\,m</m> 
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
           <me>
            \beta = m\frac{D \lambda}{a} = 0.018 \,m \quad [set\quad m=1]
           </me>
           
          </li>
          <li>
          <me>
            y = m\beta = 4\times0.018=0.072 \,m
          </me>
          
          </li>
          <li>
           <me>
            y = \frac{mD\lambda}{a}= 0.027 \,m \quad [set\quad m=\frac{3}{2}]
           </me>
           
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A diffraction grating has 500 slits per millimeter. 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            What is the angle between red light of wavelength 700 nm and violet light of wavelength 400 nm for the second order spectrum? 
          </li>
          <li>
            Does the third order spectrum overlap the second order spectrum?
          </li>
          <li>
            If a beam of green light of wavelength 550 nm passes through the grating and is projected on a wall 4 meters away, 
            what is the distance between the first order fringe and the second order fringe?
          </li>
        </ol>
          </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <me>
              \frac{N}{L} = \frac{1}{d} \Rightarrow   \frac{500}{0.001} = \frac{1}{d} \Rightarrow d=2\times10^{-6}\,m
            </me>
              <me>
              \,d\sin\theta_{1} = m\lambda_{1} \Rightarrow  2\times10^{-6} \sin\theta_{1} = (2)(700\times10^{-9}) \Rightarrow \theta_{1} = 44.4^{o}
            </me>
            <me>
              \,d\sin\theta_{2} = m\lambda_{2} \Rightarrow 2\times10^{-6} \sin\theta_{2} = (2)(400\times10^{-9}) \Rightarrow \theta_{2} = 23.6^{o}
            </me>
            <me>
              \Delta\theta = \theta_{1}-\theta_{2}=20.8^{o}
            </me>
            </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \,d\sin\theta_{3} = m\lambda_{3} \Rightarrow 2\times10^{-6} \sin\theta_{3} = (3)(400\times10^{-9})\Rightarrow \theta_{3} = 36.9^{o}
            </me>
             Since the third order red <m>\theta_{3} = 36.9^{o}</m> is less than the second order violet <m>\theta_{1} = 44.4^{o}</m>, yes.
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \,d\sin\theta_{4} = m\lambda_{4} \Rightarrow  2\times10^{-6} \sin\theta_{4} = (1)(550\times10^{-9}) \Rightarrow \theta_{4} = 16.0^{o}
            </me>
            <me>
              \tan\theta_{4} = \frac{y_{4}}{D} \Rightarrow \tan(16.0^{o}) = \frac{y_{4}}{4}  \Rightarrow y_{4}  = 1.14 \,m 
            </me>
            <me>
              \,d\sin\theta_{5} = m\lambda_{5} \Rightarrow 2\times10^{-6} \sin\theta_{5} = (2)(550\times10^{-9}) \Rightarrow \theta_{5} = 33.4^{o}
            </me>
            <me>
              \tan\theta_{5} = \frac{y_{5}}{D} \Rightarrow \tan(33.4^{o}) = \frac{y_{5}}{4}  \Rightarrow y_{5}  = 2.63 \,m
            </me>
            <me>
              \Delta y =y_{1}-y_{2}= 1.49 \,m 
            </me>
             </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
